{"summary":"Both amendments identify real persistence-integrity bugs in the current implementation.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-10-a35fc4da","decision":"accept","rationale":"The completion journal encoder writes `project_id`, `run_id`, and `plan_hash` into a raw `, `-delimited string, while the parser recovers fields by splitting on that same delimiter. The only protection is `debug_assert!`, but `ProjectId::new` and `RunId::new` still accept values containing `, ` and `plan_hash` is just a free string. In release builds a valid identifier such as `foo, bar` makes parsing fail, so `repairable_completion_event` cannot merge replayed completion events and `append_event_if_missing` falls back to appending a duplicate row instead of doing the intended idempotent repair."},{"amendment_id":"fr-10-9fd118d3","decision":"accept","rationale":"`append_task_run` serializes the supplied `TaskRunEntry` verbatim even though it separately receives the authoritative `milestone_id`. Because `TaskRunEntry.milestone_id` is still optional and missing values are only backfilled after deserialization in `read_task_runs_from_path`, callers of the public append API can still create new on-disk rows with no embedded milestone id. That violates the self-contained-entry invariant and leaves persisted lineage incomplete until some later rewrite repairs it."}]}